text:
although, i don't believe in idol worshipping but love this festival 'navratri' as it stands for women's power and their empowerment. 
it celebrates women's power to stand alone, majestically, and have an identity without her better half.
it's not about turning men's perspective soft towards women  and give respect to them coz that is something which is core value of our society and we don't need festival to realize this basic value. 
but this festival is about making women realize being fearless, be bold and raise voice against anything that breaks their rights and dignity. 
note - post is inspired by #metoo movement.' being fearless '

text:
as simple as it sounds, submitting official film for foreign language category at the oscars is actually quite complicated. (especially if we want it to get nominated, or even win!) first, the film must have entered international film festivals considered to be the darlings of hollywood. @cinesurya managed to do that by having the feature screened at tiff and cannes last year. 
second, it must be constantly talked about. not only it has to be really good by the critics(either the story or the technical aspects), the film in itself has to be very important. the past recipients of this category usually are those who spark hottest topics to be discussed. of course, 'marlina' has that #metoo momentum.

then, we need to constantly remind @theacademy to watch and vote this film by massive marketing campaigns. from the grassroots, we could post anything related with the #marlinagoestooscar hashtag, but the governent also needs to facilitate cinesurya to actualy make more content, like #foryourconsideration youtube video or a new and more profound hashtag that reminds them with important topic they should fight for, like, #marlinafightsforsexualabuse . by doing so, the voters of the academy will be reminded if a vote for marlina, is a vote for #fightsforsexualabuse #oscar #bestforeignlanguagefilm #theacademy #sataywestern #cannesfilmfestival #torontointernationalfilmfestival #marlinasipembunuhdalamempatbabak #marlinathemurdererinfouracts #marshatimothy #metoo #filmindonesia #banggafilmindonesia #indonesiadalamsinema
name: Indonesia Dalam Sinema

text:
need a reminder to vote november 6th? here's new dystopian poetry by the incredible washington, dc-based poet tara campbell, filed under politics. excerpt below; link in bio! vote november 6th. üá∫üá∏‚ú®üóû
.
in the new republic
we will call men ‚Äúsir‚Äù
or ‚Äúbaby‚Äù or ‚Äúmaster,‚Äù
whichever they prefer
at the time.
.
in the new republic
they‚Äôll only broadcast cat videos
and cooking shows
and puppy bowl
and the bachelor
(never the bachelorette)
and the bachelors will put
all the women
they‚Äôve ever wanted
into a row
and choose one of us
and choose her
and choose her
and choose her
until they tire of thrusting
their rose-red stems
into her
face.
.
in the new republic
we won‚Äôt ask for the truth
anymore
but they‚Äôll tell it to us
with a slap on the cheek
with their hands on our throats
with gleaming pistoled fists.
they‚Äôll say these new truths
are self-evident
but we‚Äôll know they‚Äôre not new.
they are ancient...
.

when i was 13 when my stepdad used to tell me i was pretty. it was okay, but he began doing it often and when we were alone. it made me uncomfortable. he used to get drunk and make me sit on his lap. i was 14 then, it was just wrong looking and feeling. he used to bite my cheeks and call me his cachetona which means "chubby cheeks". he wouldn't let me get off of his lap. he was an alcoholic and abusive to my mom. not sure if she noticed the way he was with me then. i never talked to her about it. one day after i walked home from school he was there alone.  not sure how it happened but i remember he grabbed me against the wall of his bedroom and forced a kiss on my mouth. it was so gross. i got away and ran crying to my room and locked the door. i told him i would tell mom, but i never did. i have never told anyone and now i am in my 30s. i will never ever leave him alone around my children! #metoo #nomore #metoomovement

the number of woman who are murdered every day by a current or former male partner in the us... 3 per day ‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
the number of people per minute that are physically abused by their partner... 20 per minute

the percentage of women worldwide who experience physical and or sexual abuse by an intimate partner during their lifetime... 35%
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
the percentage of lesbian women who experience domestic violence in their lifetimes... 50%
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
the number of calls placed to domestic violence hotlines every day... 20,000 calls per day
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
the number of children exposed to domestic violence every year... 10,000,000 children every year
‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢

.
i accept the plastic in our oceans and the president in our oval office. i accept women who can only be victims, and white people who can only be violent. i accept chemicals disguised as food in our supermarkets and children made to feel like fools in our schools. i accept the shame so many feel around our sexuality, and the stigma so many see around our (in)sanity.
.
not because i think any of it is ok‚Äîit‚Äôs not‚Äîbut because i know it exists and i recognize that fighting against what is, is futile. after all, it already is.
.
but it doesn‚Äôt have to continue to be.
.
and it‚Äôs only by accepting what is that i am truly free to move toward what could be.
.
and what could be, could be glorious.
.
join me, when you‚Äôre ready.
.

text: you can‚Äôt see more than 10 feet in any direction‚Äîa giant grizzly bear is somewhere in the bush nearby. we‚Äôre standing on a mound of earth... under that mound is @adam.greentree‚Äôs moose kill. adam was forced to leave the kill overnight. this mound of dirt is what we found when arrived the next morning to retrieve the meat. the grizzly had fully buried the entire moose, pissed on everything and claimed the kill for his own. the earthen mound was warm to the touch where the grizzly had been resting on it moments before. it was a dangerous situation‚Äîan eerie moment of extreme risk and indecision. do we leave the meat? do we try and take the meat back? the kill site offered no visibility; no ability to see the bear until it would be too late. we grabbed a bag of meat near the surface of the earthen mound and backed-out of the area as quickly and safely as we could. i still wonder where that bear was standing while we stood on the kill site he claimed. was he watching us? was he listening? was a 100 yards away? or was he 20 yards? how long was he going to tolerate our presence? and why wasn‚Äôt he afraid of the human scent and the gear left surrounding the kill overnight? this place is still wild‚Äîa truly savage and natural place where modern man is a naive and foreign invader. #staygritty @backcountrybcandbeyond #britishcolumbia @danwato

karnataka actress accuse actor arjun #metoo

sandalwood actress sruthi hariharan has accused actor arjun sarja of sexual harassment during the shooting of the movie ‚Äòvismaya‚Äô, according to tv reports.

this is the first instance in sandalwood (karnataka ) where an actress has named the ‚Äúperpetrator‚Äù. recently, another actress sangeetha bhat had levelled allegations against some ‚Äútop directors‚Äù but she refrained from naming anyone.

the #metoo storm first struck bollywood with tanushree dutta levelling allegations against nana patekar, her co-star in the movie ‚Äúhorn ‚Äòok‚Äô pleassss‚Äù. since then, skeletons kept tumbling out and did not even spare the union council of minister. bjp minister akbar has to resign after more than 20 female journalists filed charges against him in court.

#arjun #womem

text:
hey guys! did you know that this is what #metoo pens look like?
at work we have our pens duct taped to flowers so people don't walk away with them (customers and servers alike). and 1 in 10 guys will make a stupid "girl/not manly" pen joke. and i bite my tongue every time to not comment about their toxic masculinity. but there are 2 guys that are persistent in mentioning it. 2day one of our regulars was paying and he picked up the flower pen to sign and the man behind him offered him his man (plain) pen. the fragile man was talking about how he always talks about us getting manlier pens and how i ignore him every time. at this point the regulars that i like left and he's talking directly to me. so, again, i ignore the comment about the pens. he brought his own pen, so i don't know why he's still complaining. honestly it's cleaner that way anyway. and he goes on about how we should offer normal pens and then he mumbled "damn me too pens". and that's when i finally said something. there was a rage that started making me shake but i tried to be semi professional about it. i said "there's no need for all of that. that's highly offensive". he looks at me like i'm wrong and says "no, it's not". at this point the lady that he was with said something to him. idk what she said but it wasn't enough. so i also added that that is a serious problem and "it's nothing to joke about". and i remained professional until he left. then i had to walk out back to calm down and i started to cry. my manager had to takeover the register for a while and i felt like shit for the rest of the day. 
the times i hear comments about the pens i'm fine, but the minute you say 2 words i'm affected üò´üò°üò°

text:
@regran_ed from @sirpennypacker - üîä #smug #xenophobia ‚Äî #donaldtrump on friday brushed off a question about what evidence he has to support the claim that migrants who are reaching the southern border are "hardened criminals."
-
"oh please, don't be a baby. take a look," trump said after new york times reporter emily cochrane posed the question as he talked to journalists before attending a rally in arizona.
-
the comment from trump comes as he continually rails against democrats for current u.s. immigration policies. -
trump has repeatedly accused democrats of supporting "open borders" and spoke at length during a rally thursday in montana about a so-called "catch and release" policy allowing some migrants who reach the u.s. to stay.
-
"we have to take those people in even if they are criminals. and we have hardened criminals coming in. you think those people are perfect? they're not perfect. we have some bad people coming in, and by law, we have to take them in and then we have to -- it's called 'catch and release,' you ever hear this one?" he said.
-
#trump has ratcheted up his immigration-related rhetoric heading into the final weeks of campaigning before the november midterms.
-
this week he has taken increasing issue with a band of approximately 4,000 central americans heading toward the u.s.-mexico border.
-
"i am watching the democrat party led (because they want open borders and existing weak laws) assault on our country by guatemala, honduras and el salvador, whose leaders are doing little to stop this large flow of people, including many criminals, from entering mexico to u.s.," trump tweeted on thursday.
-
trump also has threatened to send the military to the southern border to prevent further migration.
-
"as you know i'm willing to send the military to defend our southern border if necessary, all caused because of the illegal immigration onslaught brought by the democrats because they refuse to acknowledge or change the laws," he said during a rally in montana.

text:
sexual assault is a highly common thing that still happens today. it effects both men and women, and that is what the #metoo movement is about. i, myself, say me too.
now the kavanaugh hearings had such a disturbing outcome. i believe dr. ford was being 100% truthful.
women don‚Äôt spend thousands of dollars and risk their own reputations and safety to falsely accuse men of rape or sexual assault.
who remembers the names of every woman who has spoken out against their sexual abusers/rapists?
now who can name all of the accused men? and how many of those men actually had their careers ruined?
now you can agree that women do not speak out about sexual assault for money or fame. and you can also see that this shit doesn‚Äôt ruin a man‚Äôs career ‚Äî when it most definitely should.
brett kavanaugh should not have been approved for the position in the supreme court. he is a suspected rapist and sexual abuser, and that on its own is enough to say no to this man receiving that position of such power. and also considering how emotionally unstable and immature he acted by carrying on like that in the hearings, he didn‚Äôt just let the law ‚Äúprove her wrong‚Äù if she supposedly was. and because he didn‚Äôt sit back, chill, because it didn‚Äôt actually happen, it‚Äôs very clear that he is most likely guilty and hiding something.
i appreciate strong women like dr. ford and lady gaga (and hundreds of others) who, despite all of the odds against them, have the bravery to speak up for women, sexual assault/rape survivors and what is right, and try to protect the people ‚Äî as the government and the law should be doing.
start believing women, because we are so sick and tired of society and the justice system ignoring and going against us. because that‚Äôs not humanity, nor is it justice.
love to @ladygaga ‚ù§Ô∏è

tonight was the first screening of "banged."
.
@jennaparallelpark summed up @bangedthepilot perfectly. "filmmaking is hard. telling rough stories is harder." thank you @jennaparallelpark and @lizziegwrmann for trusting me to shoot this story. sexual assault is not an easy subject to tackle but it's something that has affected many lives--family, friends, and loved ones. "banged" is a thank you to the men and women who suffer in silence as well as those who have told their rough stories.
.
last but not least, thank you to the incredible crew, especially the badass women behind the scenes. couldn't have done it without everyone of you.

text: hey guys. so today is my one year anniversary. and i can honestly say this past year has been the most challenging year of my life. one year ago today i went to a party at a friends house and had a little too much to drink. i woke up in bed and was sexually assaulted by one of my best friends. after that i battled with anxiety and depression from the event along with having ptsd. i developed an addiction to self harm, stopped then relapsed in february after i became suicidal. this past year changed me but looking back, i realize how much stronger it made me. i know i‚Äôm not the same person i was a year ago and i‚Äôm 100% sure it is because of the trauma i experienced. and i want to take the time to tell all the survivors reading this that you are not alone. i know it‚Äôs challenging but it does get better. please give yourself time to heal and forgive yourself. what happened to you is not your fault. i love you and am here for you. ‚ù§Ô∏è love rissy.  #love #youareenough #loveyourselffirst #quotes #quotesdaily #inspiration #sexualassault #empowerment  #survivor #metoo #metoomovement #quitthisshit #recovery #feminist #feminism #feministquote  #trauma #female #inspirationalquote #equality #trigger #triggerwarning #assault #ptsd #mybodymychoice #consent #endrapeculture #timesup

text:
i feel like we don't have a strong framework for consensual activities within our current society. it's very apparent by what is reflected in the macrocosm of our world currently. we've been witnessing this long before the #metoomovement even started and will be continually challenged in this day and age as the dark energy of an unbalanced society gets pushed up against by voices that can no longer keep quiet. 
i believe in the ability to transform.
i believe in the ability to shift energy.
i believe in the capacity for people to unlearn there past.
i believe in survivors.
i believe in personal and collective accountability. 
and most importantly i believe in creating a society where consent culture is the new standard. 
here you'll find a really potent image by the work of dr. betty martin. 
in any instance of touch, there are two factors: who is doing and who is it for. those two factors combine in four ways (quadrants). each quadrant presents it's own challenges, lessons and joys. the circle represents your agreement. inside the circle there is a gift given and a gift received. outside the circle (without consent) the same action is shown when the shadow side of that interaction is expressed.

educate. sublimate. make change!

#consent #metoo #sexuality #sacralempowerment #bodypositive #sexposi #somaticsexeducation #sexualhealth #consentculture #sacredsexuality

educate. sublimate. make change!

text:
when you think you've failed at something.
..
some days things just aren't going right. we stumble, we fall, we do what we know we shouldn't even sometimes deliberately. that was me yesterday... thinking about it today and what happened, i realize that i just put too much on my plate for the day and i burnt myself out by the evening and turned to food for comfort (my old ways), instead of turning to god and trying to figure out what was going on within me.
..
i stayed up late, overate and watched netflix until i was uncomfortable and felt like crap. this doesn't happen very often anymore thanks to the lords amazing help but when it does i feel ashamed and embarrassed.
..
i feel like i can't share this with anyone, they will think i'm a joke. but the reality is, that if i don't share my struggles, no one will know that i struggle, they will only see the side i show them and think that i have this perfect life.
..
being genuine and real in both my faith and life is something i really strive for and i just want to tell you, i struggle too. i have bad eating days, bad depression days, days where i just don't want to do anything, days where the passion just isn't there, the difference between now and then though, is i don't stay there for days on end.
..
i used to be someone who would go on a binge streak if i overate, but today i just ate like i normally eat and worked out like i normally would have worked out. i didn't starve myself, i didn't punish myself with two workouts, i just got right back on track. it was a new day, god gives new mercies each morning, i chose to repent and walk into this day with god and get back up after i fell. you can choose that too. give yourself grace, but don't stay in that pit. get out and get back on your path. ‚ù§üëç you got this.

text: warning: an honest post. seems there are seasons for ‚Äòjourneyroads‚Äô. october is a season i love. the first photo we were soaking up afternoon rays in venice beach ca. the latter a deep sigh to life with lupus. it is very hard for anyone to comprehend stress is to a person with lupus as measles is to a pregnant woman- threatening and dangerous. it is a juggernaut for families, someone‚Äôs moodswing can cause a price. responsibility to refrain from reaction requires effort, training and practice. holding a space for others requires effort, training and space‚Äîsome call it charity, some call it care, some call it love, some call it burden, some call it humanity. labels weary me. so i say, just be good to each other, forgive each other, love can win, every time. not everyone believes in a savior. i do. unapologetically. he who has suffered in the house of his own friends- understands. how i choose to use this knowledge, is up to me.  frustration with illness serves no purpose. i have been gifted life several, several times. as an infant surviving brain surgery in the sixties, as a toddler escaping a cross dresser with an ice pick unscathed, as a teen surviving a kidnapper and rapist. as an adult surviving multiple chronic illness and growth‚Äîstaying in the game and not losing hope.  life isn‚Äôt for the timid. these skills have to be learned. learning takes failing. failing takes forgiving. forgiving takes loving. loving is everything.  i believe, love wins every time. let love win. #kiowaroamer #native #lupus #metoo #love #hope #faith #kindness #blessed #takeaminute #healedpeopehealpeople #bekind #takeiteasy #travel

text:
feminism- what a controversial word!!! i was speaking with some female friends the other day and the conversation turned to feminism. i was surprised to learn that many women would never publicly consider themselves feminists. i was even more shocked at the voice in my head that was agreeing with them! 'feminism' these days is almost as dirty a word as the word 'witch'! üåôso it got me to thinking, why do we as modern day women want to distance ourselves from the very women who came before us, paved the way, and made our reality possible through their relentless courage and standing ground? i'm inclined to think it comes back to the same reason we don't want to identify as witches in public... fear of being seen as 'too much', 'too out there', 'a man hater','annoying', 'loud', 'opinionated', etc. after all these years and my relativly free upbringing, i still have patriarchial conditioning that keeps me from identifying with 'that kind of woman'. üåôcheck out the netflix documentary feminists: what were they thinking. i cried the whole way through with deep pride of the amazing women who stood up and said enough is enough for my freedom. i also looked up the actual laws that changed because of these feminists. btw... these are all rights i take for granted everyday. sigh... üåôcheck out these 9 things we couldn't do before women started burning their bras:

1. keep a job if pregnant

2. report sexual harassment

3.¬†be allowed to participate in all sports and educational opportunities

4. refuse to have sex with husband

5. get a credit card

6. get a divorce with ease

7. get an abortion

8. claim rape as a crime of violence

9.¬†be acknowledged in the boston marathon

i'm proud of these women and these accomplishments and i'm declaring i'm proud to be a feminist too!  #humanity #loveistheway #feminism #witch #metoo #heforshe #anewearth #spiritualwoman #spiritualwomen #wokeaf #itsfeminism

text: this song is the opener of my upcoming album. i‚Äôve been trying, in so many ways over the last 15 years, to write this song and the closing song of the record. they both talk about my childhood sexual trauma and abuse. this song is a sort of overture that sets the tone for the honesty of this album. in the wake of the kavanaugh hearings and the #metoo movement, i felt that i had to speak up in a louder, more direct way. it‚Äôs time we all tell our stories and it‚Äôs time i tell mine, in its entirety. life is short and can be out of your control, but your voice doesn‚Äôt have to be. i love you all and am so honored to be on this planet and on this journey with you. burn the patriarchy to the ground so we can kick up the ashes while we dance in the new age. and please, please, please vote on november 6th. üíïüëªüéÉ

text:
i had the amazing opportunity yesterday to sing for an organization that has supported me, my family and the community of saskatoon.

7 years ago shortly after graduating i was raped.
i don‚Äôt like to talk about it. i feel embarrassed and i‚Äôm scared of what people will think.
so i don‚Äôt share this so people know it happened. i write this because it is my heart that people, like me, know there is hope.

in trauma there is darkness.
in hurt there is hopelessness.
in shame there is hiding.
but-
you are not ruined or wrecked.
you are not used or trash.
you are not your body.
you are precious.
you are beautiful.
you are powerful and you are loved.
believe in yourself and in your body and minds ability to heal.
you are worth it.
say it over and over to yourself everyday until you believe it.
you are worth it. 
you‚Äôre free. üïä‚ú®‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
day 20-breakable, this was a piece that meant a lot to me. when i was 14 i suffered sexual abuse at the hands of someone i trusted. i endured this from 14-18. i still have nightmares, and anxiety, and even guilt. i know now that what i went through was not my fault, but that of someone sick. i'm not healed yet, not even close, but i'm getting there, and i know it's ok not to have everything figured our right now. for anyone suffering, or having suffered it, you are not alone. and you are strong enough to get through this. you are worth something. and it is not your fault. i have listed the national sexual assault hotline and national suicide prevention hotline below. #inktober#inktober2018#jakeparker#survivor#metoo

national sexual assault hotline: 1-800-656-4673

national suicide prevention hotline: 1-800-273-8255

text:
to my husband,
there have been some very high highs and some very low lows but never have i questioned anything. i know that god placed you in my life and this roller coaster ride will bring us places we cannot yet imagine. i thought this year would feel like another year in our relationship, i was wrong. this year was full of getting to know you as my husband and understanding what it is to be a wife‚Äî and everything felt new and different.  everyone said it would be the same and boy they were wrong. it wasn‚Äôt always easy but there was always so much love, support, and constant reality checks (thanks ma & wendy üòÇ). expectations are nice but living in the moment with you is where i prefer to be for the rest of our eternity. 
happy anniversary mr. neal!!
forever & always,
candace v neal ‚ù§Ô∏è

last night i yelled at a grown man for fake dropping his phone behind me while i did deadlifts. he fake dropped it so he could stare at my ass while he picked it up. as if i couldn't see him in the mirror. i shouted dont look at me! at the top of my 10th rep for 200lbs.

scared the crap out of him and he ran. the rest of my deadlifts were fueled by rage and they went great! and guess what, i'm not gonna stop making myself look pretty or dress differently or try to hide or feel shame. its not my fault hes a gross human. so here i am. makeup done and hair up!

text:
be nice.
don't yell.
don't make a scene.

i've said these words so many times that i know my girls try to live up to them... until my daughter let's me know that she was in a conversation with an older person and she was uncomfortable and didn't know what to do.

fail mom. fail.

she needs to know that she has a voice. that she can leave. that she can tell someone she's not comfortable.

this time it was relatively harmless, teasing about a boy, but what about when it's inappropriate or dangerous?

i've got to give her words that she can use to #speakup.

she needs to know that she gets to decide.

how about:
"i'm not comfortable with this conversation, can we talk about something else." or. "this isn't making me feel very good. can we talk about something different?" or. "i'm going to head out, i've got to work on a project." or "mom, i don't like this." my heart hurts as i type the last one. i didn't see her cues and the conversation was 'harmless' but she felt stuck and as though she couldn't get out.

any other ideas? what words can you give your daughter so she can use her voice to set and protect her boundaries?

#momofthreegirls #girlschangingtheworld #spreadlove #metoo

she‚Äôs not the only actress who‚Äôs questioning disney movies. keira knightley recently told ellen degeneres that her 3-year-old daughter, edie, is ‚Äúbanned‚Äù from watching ‚Äúcinderella‚Äù and ‚Äúthe little mermaid.‚Äù the 33-year-old actress said the 1950s cinderella character ‚Äúwaits around for a rich guy to rescue her. don‚Äôt! rescue yourself. obviously!‚Äù and when it came to ‚Äúthe little mermaid,‚Äù knightley questioned the film‚Äôs message about relying on a ‚Äúprince charming.‚Äù ‚Äúand this is the one that i‚Äôm quite annoyed about because i really like the film, but ‚Äòlittle mermaid,‚Äô‚Äù she said. ‚Äúi mean, the songs are great, but do not give your voice up for a man. hello.‚Äù #snowwhite #kristinbell #littlemermaid #disney #girls #fantasy #wrongmessage #princecharming #princess #cinderella #hollywood

text:
me too?
20‚Äù x 24‚Äù
oil on canvas $480
.
this painting has been a long time coming for me, i just didn‚Äôt know what it would look like until a few weeks ago. .
6 years ago i thought it was all normal: the pressure, the guilt, the fighting, the hiding. .
4 years ago i thought i broke free but now i was putting pressure on myself, i was guilting myself, i was doubting anything bad had happened still. .
1 year ago the pressure was gone, the guilt gone. the doubt that anything bad had happened was still there. .
2 weeks ago i felt even harder for all the victims. 2 weeks ago the doubt began to crack. could this have really happened to me too?

yesterday the @nytimes failed to mention @margotnorton, co-curator of the #sarahlucas survey at the @newmuseum, instead crediting #massimilianogioni as the sole curator. in the same moment their lengthy review thanked a man who ‚Äúdevoted three floors to a woman‚Äôs work,‚Äù they erased the woman from art history. after an outcry on social media, today the times printed a terse correction. is that enough?
.
.
#metoo #notsurprised #correcttherecord #intellectuallaborisreallabor
for more on this phenomenon, see @michellemillarfisher's essay in @hyperallergic
https://hyperallergic.com/453438/acknowledging-the-intellectual-labor-of-curators-in-a-museum/
the author was #marthaschwendener but as many have pointed out, this is a trend for the nyt and quite possibly something that happened in editorial.

text:
this is who i work for.
all day. every day.
this version of me is a warrior who almost didn‚Äôt make it.  i will protect her first. i promised her that i would do that. that it was safe for her now. i don‚Äôt have any tolerance for people who can‚Äôt control their energy, emotions or be responsible and accountable for their actions. zero.  zero tolerance for not being accountable in my personal life and relationships. there‚Äôs been enough of that in her life.
for a survivor boundaries are often all we have. she‚Äôs had enough disappointment for lifetimes and if it is within my control to protect her from more, i will do it without any regret. you are not the judge of what is acceptable to me. i am. she never had a choice, we made it out and i promised my little self she would be safe if she came back, and i protect her at any cost with fierce compassion. 
stay strong girls. this transition we are going through is one of many. hold on by the roots of your ancestry, and by the power that exists in the divine feminine. we will prevail. we are going to be the strongest generations of women this planet may have ever seen.

text:
some days my depression is like being in a room filled with thick smoke.
like i know a fire has started somewhere but i don‚Äôt know what‚Äôs set it off or why or how.
i can‚Äôt really see where i‚Äôm going and it‚Äôs hard to move.
i don‚Äôt know where my goal is but i know i have a way out somewhere.
it takes my breath away but it only makes me more determined to carry on.
i can‚Äôt see or focus on other things but how to survive. i have my daughter and my girlfriend but the rest is a blur.
survival mode kicks in and i‚Äôm sorry. 
i‚Äôm sorry if i don‚Äôt see you much or if i don‚Äôt text you much when i‚Äôm depressed. i know you are with me but i‚Äôve lost you in the smoke. 
i can‚Äôt see you right now i‚Äôm just focusing on surviving.
just keep calling and i will find you again, don‚Äôt leave and it will be easier to reach out.
my hobbies are lost in the smoke. 
my motivation, lack of self care. 
but i will find them again.
-
my anxiety is a smoke alarm, it‚Äôs an overbearing amount of panic. it tells me i need to get out, it tells me if i don‚Äôt do something now i will die. 
my anxiety is like a smoke alarm because anything can set it off, it can be a bit of steam or a big fire and my body reacts the same. so when i hear this fire alarm my body thinks the worst. my body doesn‚Äôt know what to do apart from panic, my palms sweat and my heart races. don‚Äôt tell me it‚Äôs just a panic attack because in the moment i can‚Äôt tell what has set it off and i‚Äôm just trying to survive. ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
the story goes like this
iii:

he told me, ‚Äúus canadians have to stick together‚Äù and that he‚Äôd be someone i could count on being so far from home in a new city. he was also from toronto. we were connected through a few degrees of separation. the common denominator was that we were both living in chicago for work. i remember i trusted him because of the friends of friends that we had in common. i trusted him because he was from home. i trusted him because he was socially awkward. i trusted him because he talked about places in toronto which manifested familiarity.

i remember feeling a body behind mine that wasn‚Äôt there when i went to sleep. i remember feeling hot breath on the back of my neck that wasn‚Äôt safe, that wasn‚Äôt from my dog. i remember realizing that my pants were not on and that the snaps of my bodysuit were undone. ‚Äútell me you want me to fuck you.‚Äù his quiet voice crept into my left ear and washed down my shoulder and then hardened like a plum pit in my stomach.

my body froze. i felt paralyzed. my mouth opened but i couldn‚Äôt say a word. have you ever wanted to scream but nothing came out?

you may be wondering what events led up to these moments, but they don‚Äôt matter.

what matters is that i did not consent.

what matters is what was taken.

what matters is what followed.

the hospital kept the bodysuit i fell asleep in and the underwear i wore the next morning as evidence. i wore the complimentary white gauze hospital briefs home under my jogging pants, but quickly undressed and ran a hot bath.

i called my best friend.

text:
i share my story with raw authenticity because i know one simple truth:‚†Ä
‚†Ä
engaging in the story of others changes us.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
we grow in processing our own stories when others share theirs. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
we move from apathy to empathy when we see the humanity of people who aren‚Äôt like us. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
we learn to be motivated by love, not fear, when we see others who have lived through hell and they are alive and free. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
my story is literally about me but it is also literally about you.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
after the horrors of a childhood with every kind of abuse and abject poverty, instead of being dead, i am alive.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
after the trauma of soul-crushingly oppressive religion and spiritual abuse, i am free.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
join me in embracing the beauty that is learning how to be transparently & powerfully you.‚†Ä

text:
sometimes it's just words, othertimes it's so much more. 
8 months later they finally released these e-fits. its taken me a couple of weeks to stop looking at the comments people have left, and a couple of weeks to realise i can't ignore the situation completely. 8 months later and pretty much everyone has moved on with their lives, except me. i still have to see where this happened every single day out of my window. i have to go home knowing there is no escape from this, replaying the same day in my head every morning and every single evening without choice, without fail. 
the worst part isn't living in the past, it's trying to move forward, it's trying to convince yourself you're worth anything at all, it's that sinking feeling in your chest you have to live with everyday, it's the feeling of wanting to tell someone absolutely everything but not having the words to explain how much you hurt, or how much help you need to fix it. 
it's always speaking your truth that hurts the most. 
#speakyourtruth 
#metoo

text:
üëãover the past few weeks there has been a slew of new friends and followers! wanted to quickly introduce myself and say, hello!üëã üôãi‚Äôm melissa ann! author/coach/advocate. üåü in 2018 i took a leap and chose to live by the motto, ‚Äúif you do not see her, you have to #beher.‚Äù the #metoo movement encouraged me to own my story of life after sexual assault.¬† it also inspired me to take the conversation a step further and begin the dialogue of how do we heal on an individual and collective level. üíó in being her, i've chosen to remove the masks and share my truth. with the intention of letting other survivors know they are not alone. i'm here to... see you, hear, and love you. because i am you! üìöthis led me to writing, ‚Äúwho will love me? a holistic approach to building meaningful relationships.‚Äù (currently available for pre-order on amazon.) üíïi‚Äôm a personal empowerment coach, supporting women to build meaningful relationships after sexual assault. üëìschool is my happy place, (really the library is!) currently i‚Äôm a doctoral student in leadership studies. üêáfun facts: i have a rabbit named gypsy. love to hula hoop. and am addicted to no bake cookies. üíìlove,

melissa ann

text:
the process of conscious uncoupling.
üôèüèª
divorce is a traumatic and difficult decision for all parties.

i know, because i‚Äôm going through it, but i prefer the phrase gwyneth paltrow and chris martin coined in 2014 as ‚Äòconscious uncoupling‚Äô. the act of ending a marriage or relationship in a way that is viewed as a positive step by both parties, who believe their lives will be better for doing so, as opposed to the hot mess that often happens during a divorce.
‚ù£Ô∏è
too often we hide from our weakness and pain and wait to share the story until we are through the other side. we tell the tale of struggle and how we overcame victoriously, but how often do we just show up to our own vulnerability?
üôÑ
to be real with you, this is simultaneously the worst and the best time of my life. it is the worst because as you can imagine, emotions are surfacing, things are changing, i am leaving someone i have been in a relationship with for ten years. but i also feel as though i am evolving, listening to what my soul is telling me and through this discomfort, i feel an expansion within, as my personality and soul align a little closer to my personal truth.
‚ù£Ô∏è
i have full respect for people that choose to get married and stay together their whole lives. i think about my great-grandmother, my grandma and even my parents. they did it‚Ä¶ so am i a failure if i didn‚Äôt?
üîÆ
perhaps to some, but to me, i‚Äôm a failure if i don‚Äôt listen to my inner guidance, if i refuse to walk my path because it's scary and unfamiliar, then i fail myself. ü¶ã
and i am forever grateful to the women that came before me, for the women that stayed in relationships because they had no option to work or provide for their families, to the women that suffered abusive, violent relationships, and are still suffering. we owe it to them to be true to ourselves.
‚ù£Ô∏è
so i am marrying myself and adopting a new name heather jesse ray.
‚ù£Ô∏è
jesse was the name of my great-grandmother who emigrated to australia in 1927 and means witness of god.
‚ù£Ô∏è
ray because that's what we are, rays of light, shining through the illusion of what is.

that‚Äôs it, my authentic truth about an experience that is alchemizing. ‚ù£Ô∏è‚ù£Ô∏è‚ù£Ô∏è

text: the past few days, multiple friends and colleagues have come forward in their stories of sexual assault. of how horrible it is, and how much it can scare a person. it doesn‚Äôt matter when it happened. it doesn‚Äôt matter what you were wearing. it doesn‚Äôt matter what gender you are. it happened to someone. it scared someone. these brave people have encouraged and supported me to come forward with my own story. the fact that it happened to me too. it happened years ago, but i still remember. i remember the fear and confusion of what was going on. i remember the pain. i remember not knowing what to do, and feeling as though if i told someone it would be my fault. that i would be the blame, and that no one would believe me. i remember crying myself asleep for nights on end. i never reported him because i felt like i would ruin someone else‚Äôs life. it felt like i was a shadow of my former self. that the darkness and pain was overwhelming and took to control of who i was. it owned me, as if his handprints were forever there even if they physically weren‚Äôt. to this day there are times i don‚Äôt feel worthy of love. but that‚Äôs not true. and i realize that it. i realize what he did was wrong, that i‚Äôm still beautiful even though that happened, and that there‚Äôs no shame in sharing my story. i realized how important it is not only to myself, but for others. i want to stress that if you ever need anyone, i am here. i am here for you. i will support you, i will fight for you, and i will listen. we are in this together, and our voices will bring change. i love you. #metoo #speakup #vote

text:
don‚Äôt stay silent. it‚Äôs time to #speakup ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
october is national domestic violence awareness month, which first began in 1981 by the national coalition against domestic violence as a day of unity to connect battered women‚Äôs advocates across the country.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
domestic violence affects millions, both women and men, of every race, religion, culture and status. it‚Äôs not just punches and black eyes -- it‚Äôs yelling, humiliation, stalking, manipulation, coercion, threats and isolation. it‚Äôs stealing a paycheck, keeping tabs online, non-stop texting, constant use the silent treatment, or calling someone stupid so often they believe it.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
since the violence against women act passed in 1994, we‚Äôve come a long way. this landmark legislation, led by then senator joe biden, combined new provisions that hold offenders accountable and provide programs and services for victims. between 1993 and 2010, the overall rate of domestic violence dropped nearly two-thirds and state laws have reformed to address issues such as dating abuse in the workplace, stalking, employment discrimination and more.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
every october, we rededicate ourselves to breaking the cycle. nearly three out of four americans personally know someone who is or has been a victim of domestic violence. now is time to take a stand. support survivors and speak out against domestic violence.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
if you need assistance or want to talk to someone about domestic violence, call 1-866-331-9474 to speak with a trained peer advocate.

‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
domestic violence affects millions, both women and men, of every race, religion, culture and status. it‚Äôs not just punches and black eyes -- it‚Äôs yelling, humiliation, stalking, manipulation, coercion, threats and isolation. it‚Äôs stealing a paycheck, keeping tabs online, non-stop texting, constant use the silent treatment, or calling someone stupid so often they believe it.

since the violence against women act passed in 1994, we‚Äôve come a long way. this landmark legislation, led by then senator joe biden, combined new provisions that hold offenders accountable and provide programs and services for victims. between 1993 and 2010, the overall rate of domestic violence dropped nearly two-thirds and state laws have reformed to address issues such as dating abuse in the workplace, stalking, employment discrimination and more.

every october, we rededicate ourselves to breaking the cycle. nearly three out of four americans personally know someone who is or has been a victim of domestic violence. now is time to take a stand. suppo survivors and speak out against domestic violence.

text:
dear diary, 
there are days when i feel really lucky and gratefull for the people and things that i have  around me. but i also have a feeling that the presence of certain people and things will not last for ever. i remember well most of all my favorite sweaters, pens and notebooks, certain pictures, books and recordigns, coffee blends and night routines. i wish there could be some sort of a better way to keep and store the momories than just thoughts and worlds. thanks god, there's poetry and music. 
talking about poetry, diary, it seems like throughout this autumn i will be feeding you with robert frost. because he leaves so much space for thought between his lines. ‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
nothing gold can stay
robert frost,¬†1874¬†-¬†1963 ¬´¬†nature‚Äôs first green is gold, 
her hardest hue to hold. 
her early leaf‚Äôs a flower; 
but only so an hour. 
then leaf subsides to leaf. 
so eden sank to grief, 
so dawn goes down to day. 
nothing gold can stay.¬†¬ª

dear diary, 
there are days when i feel really lucky and gratefull for the people and things that i have  around me. but i also have a feeling that the presence of certain people and things will not last for ever. i remember well most of all my favorite sweaters, pens and notebooks, certain pictures, books and recordigns, coffee blends and night routines. i wish there could be some sort of a better way to keep and store the momories than just thoughts and worlds. thanks god, there's poetry and music. 
talking about poetry, diary, it seems like throughout this autumn i will be feeding you with robert frost. because he leaves so much space for thought between his lines. ‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
nothing gold can stay
robert frost,¬†1874¬†-¬†1963 ¬´¬†nature‚Äôs first green is gold, 
her hardest hue to hold. 
her early leaf‚Äôs a flower; 
but only so an hour. 
then leaf subsides to leaf. 
so eden sank to grief, 
so dawn goes down to day. 
nothing gold can stay.¬†¬ª

text:
day 2 instagram take-over by kali d‚Äôagostinis üåªüåªüåª -
today i want to share what i care about. i am passionate about female empowerment (of course) and absolutely love everything that livegirl stands for. we absolutely positively need more women in leadership positions. we must support girls at a young age to bust gender stereotypes and create equal opportunities. through livegirl and @sacredheartuniversity, i recently had an opportunity to interview aly raisman, a true female empowerment role model. @alyraisman is a champion on and off the floor. i asked her what bravery means to her and she answered, ‚Äúliving a brave life is doing what makes you happy and being your best self.‚Äù i strongly recommend that you read aly‚Äôs book, ‚Äúfierce: how competing for myself changed everything‚Äù. aly has become an advocate for the #metoo movement and victims of sexual abuse. she spoke to a packed auditorium at shu, where students lined up at microphones to ask about her gymnastics career and how she deals with her own trauma while helping others. her words stuck with me. ‚Äúi feel strongly that the change starts with each and every single one of you. i think men and women should be equal and protect each other. if you see anything suspicious, report it.‚Äù -
i am also passionate about my sorority and the chi omega/make-a-wish alliance. a wish granted not only provides hope, strength and joy to a child and their family, but it can provide a wish child with the ability and willingness to comply with difficult medical treatments, and the hope gained by that wish often improves a child‚Äôs physical health. watch my instagram story to learn more and get involved! #whaticareabout #instagramtakeover #femaleempowerment #alyraisman #makeawish #nonprofit #ct #sacredheartuniversity #chiomega

text:
don‚Äôt hide your sexy! because women are expected to be perfect in ‚Äî well, every possible way, we often do things to hide our imperfections.
and we often do these things without even knowing that we're doing them to begin with.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
but here's a crazy idea: let's *embrace* our whole selves, as perfectly imperfect as we are, and encourage others to do the same. here are seven things we do to hide our bodies that we don't ever have to do again.
1. suck in our stomachs.
2. try to distract people from our problem areas.
3. constantly adjusting our clothes. 
4. make ‚Äúskinny arms‚Äù in photos.
5. take photos that don‚Äôt show our bodies at all.
6. keep our limbs covered.
7. wear a size too small.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
don't try to convince yourself you're a size 0 if you're a 2, or an 18 if you're a 20. not only is it more uncomfortable to try to fit into too-small clothing, but owning whatever size your body fits in best is empowering af.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
so get on out here, you, and own your you-ness!

text:
#read & #share on my way to bangalore, and today i'll pen down something. call me a emotional fool that's fine. 
i want to say that people always feel that an abusive relationship is all about bleeding and scars. but abuse can be emotional too. when you're being told you're ugly, you're weak, you're  hard to love and many such things. that's not true, but when you're constantly told negative stuff it's obvious you'll doubt yourself. but i'll say don't let someone's opinion rule you. coz they ll destroy you and whomever they meet. so you have to save yourself. 
don't get fooled by someone just coz they say you're wrong don't let people manipulate your love for them and demean you. you have to learn how to come out of a toxic relationship. you might fight, cry and break your head and lose sleep but it will honestly won't help rather you'll get dark circles. so learn to draw a line. just know if they care, they will not hurt you in first place. and don't let them call you weak coz u love them, never!  #abusiverelationship #depression #realstory #womenempowerment #saynotoabuse #speakup #blogger #mystory #beyourownhero #writeaway #feelings #spreadtheword #allmysingleladies #metoo #metoomovement

text:
scorched

my expectations of love
were scorched by the fire in your eyes.

you desired something 
that i wouldn't give,
to a stranger, on the bus.

my skin was scorched
in the places
your hands reached.

my throat burned
before a single utterance
of dissent could be voiced.

now i fear.
i fear the bus,
the people on it.

for when i've spoken
i've been told
stories of when it happened 
to 'me too'. .
.
.

text:
#metoo
____
something really bad happened to me a few days ago. i was attacked and nearly raped in morocco - a country that i‚Äôve called my home for the past two months. 
____
it happened in a town where i‚Äôve felt safest in morocco and on a street i had walked so many times before. a guy came out of nowhere, grabbed my face and kissed me and then pushed me to the ground. he was on top of me and was holding my mouth so that i wouldn‚Äôt scream. 
____
i was lucky and i could still fight back - some people can‚Äôt when they go into shock. i tried to kick him and get his hands off my face so that i could scream. finally, i managed to escape. 
____
i‚Äôm an avid solo female traveler but i would lie if i said that traveling is the same for me men and women. it‚Äôs not. women have to worry about things men don‚Äôt need to - how to dress, is it safe to walk alone/after dark etc. and the amounts of cat calling and sexual harassment we have to deal with every day is horrendous. 
____
for all the solo female travelers out there, stay safe and strong! ‚ù§Ô∏è i still have scars on my face from the attack but the deepest scars are the psychological ones.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
trouble mounts for akbar ‚Äì more than a dozen women bonds with priya ramani

in a  dramatic development that could upset bjp minister  akbar‚Äôs  strategy  more than a dozen  women journalists fused as a force  and have urged the court to hear their testimonies against mj akbar, claiming many of  them suffered sexual harassment by the minister and others have been a witness to it.

a group of current and former journalists employed by the asian age, a newspaper that was once headed and edited by mj akbar who is now  bjp  union minister accused of sexually harassing at least 10 of the former colleagues  issued a joint statement  urging a delhi court to accept their testimonies in the case.

bjp minister  akbar has filed a criminal defamation suit against journalist priya ramani, the first woman to accuse him of sexual harassment. the lawsuit said ramani ‚Äúintentionally put forward malicious, fabricated and salacious‚Äù allegations to harm the former editor‚Äôs reputation.

ramani has said she is ‚Äúready to fight allegations of defamation laid against me, as truth and the absolute truth is my only defence.

after minister filed defamation suit  ramani got surprise support  from twitterati with crowd fund to take on m.j.akbar  now additionally ramani  got support from  17 journalists and they  said ‚Äúms ramani is not alone in her fight. we would request the honourable court hearing the defamation case to also consider testimonies of sexual harassment of some of us at the hands of the petitioner, as also of the other signatories who bore witness to this harassment.‚Äù the patiala house court has listed the criminal defamation case for thursday.

in his complaint, akbar said it was apparent that a false narrative against him was being circulated in a motivated manner and for the fulfilment of an agenda.

the congress and several journalist bodies in india have called for akbar‚Äôs removal from the government over the allegations. but at the time of election year the bjp strong support for akbar is going to cost the party a lot says  political  analysts

text: while chatting with my friend @gemitasamarra about my time in morocco, it occurred to me how little of the country i was able to see. despite living there for several months in my early 20s, i‚Äôve never felt as warmly about morocco as i have about other places i‚Äôve lived. in large part, i think that comes down to the horrific street harassment i endured whilst there. it made me afraid to look up from the ground when i walked, worried i might make eye contact with a man who would take a stray glance as an invitation to follow me down the street, whisper in my ear, or brush his hand against my body. it‚Äôs a shame to have such a dark cloud hanging over my memories of a place. it‚Äôs a reminder, though, that whatever it means to be a woman these days, it shapes the world we live in. i wonder what it would be like to explore the way a man does - utterly unafraid and unaware of the danger posed by looking up.

text:
it‚Äôs not enough to wear a ribbon. be the difference you want to see in the world. ask your friends if something seems off. don‚Äôt give up talking to them about it - they may be in denial or have been threatened to not tell anyone about what‚Äôs really going on. your constant support can be a light in a very, very dark world. my name is jamie, i was in an abusive relationship for three years with a guy named ali bagheri. he continued to abuse me for two more years after we had officially broke up. he blackmailed me, stalked me, threatened me into telling no one about what he had done. he told me i was the abusive one. he told me that he would kill him self if i stopped talking to him. he showed up at my work. he showed up at my home. he hacked my email and social media accounts. he terrorized me for five years. i‚Äôm not going to hide his identity - or his crimes - anymore. this is my story to tell. and you bet i‚Äôm going to tell it.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
grandma dirt

zero to hero

they are right to fear us

wandering witch

switch bitch

we're the weird sisters

challenge you

change you

rearrange you

we're hearing the call

to burn this down

rise up

the revolution starts at midnight

sisters, we take our own pain away

cause we can't use it anymore

it's the age of consent

and we don't comply
.
.
.

text:
‚Äúthe most disrespected person in america is the black woman. the most unprotected person in america is the black woman. the most neglected person in america is the black woman.‚Äù malcom x
-
black women disproportionately experience violence at home, at school, on the job, and in their neighborhoods.
-
they also suffer from many sexist stereotypes:
- the mammy, the poor maid or nurse who takes care of white houses and children.
- the aggressive, hostile, loud, bossy and emasculating woman.
- the hypersexual bad girl, gold digger, sexually aggressive, that allows men to think they can abuse them. this image is largely conveyed by hip hop, which provides a poor role model for young black girls to indentify with.
-
yes, black women are powerful but they still struggle with getting the recognition that they deserve both within and outside of the black community.
source: "the sisters are alright: changing the broken narrative of black women in america" by tamara winfrey harris.

not my art but just gonna leave this here as a reminder. i do what i want. dress how i want. talk how i want. because i can, and because we can, and (w)e should.
we are powerful beings of nature and we should totally push the boundaries of what other people consider to be ‚Äúacceptable.‚Äù in all aspects. you are not only acceptable, but exceptional. ‚ú® and you determine your own boundaries. do not accept otherwise. from anyone.
you do not have to be nice to everyone ‚Äúbecause it‚Äôs lady-like‚Äù and especially people who disrespect or try to belittle you. do not be afraid to unleash that attitude girl because that is a part of womanhood. it has to be. claim your respect. üò§
you don‚Äôt ‚Äúowe‚Äù a damn thing to anyone just because they said so. this is your life, your world, it is no one else‚Äôs place to judge or dictate what you do or want. you choose freely, and f what anyone has to say or think about it. if someone doesn‚Äôt ‚Äúapprove,‚Äù good üëèüèº rub it in their face. you run this bishh and people can either accept it or mind their business (that‚Äôs why we have eyelids that shut and fingers that scroll üòò).
and the biggest step back that you can take as a feminist, is when you let a man feel as though he has any kind of authority over you. you are an equal and you are more than worthy. üñïüèº middle fingers up to anyone who makes you feel inferior or question your worth üñïüèº you got better things to do and not enough time to waste sis...
(and yes, they will make jokes and try to make you question what you believe in ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è that‚Äôs fear and jealousy talking, possibly even admiration.) #metoo #feminist #feminism
.

text:
you may wonder why i post so many things about empowerment and giving ourselves permission to set boundaries and stand up for ourselves. it probably comes as no surprise, it's something i have struggled with my entire life. feeling small, feeling insignificant, feeling undeserving, afraid to speak up. and it became a problem. i found myself in relationships that were abusive, jobs that left me drained and burned out, feeling depressed because i felt i didn't belong in this world. further, it also caused unspoken built-up resentment in my relationships, leaving most people bewildered and surprised that i was ever upset with them. i wasn't being authentic, i wasn't being myself because of feelings of unworthiness and fear. and at the root of it was the belief that my life didn't matter. .
.
there are messages we receive from media, our culture, our families, through daily micro and macro interactions that our lives don't matter. that's why the black lives matter and me too movement (just as two of many examples) are so important, because that is the message day in and day out that other lives are more important than our lives and this creates a collective oppression, suppression, depression on a mass scale. and we internalize these messages, we start to believe them and then we are told we are crazy or lying if we ever find the bravery to speak the truth.
.
.
so how do we find a way through? perhaps it's my social work background but a cultural and global shift is needed in this very polarized world. and also i think it's important to look at the internalized messages we have swallowed and begin to give voice to our truths. there is power in knowing what you know and speaking your truth in the face of others who take an opposing position. your truth is valid, your feelings don't need an explanation or justification. you owe it to yourself and others to take a stand for who you are and what you believe in. and observe how others respond to you, it will tell you a lot about them. we go on and on about self care, to me this is the ultimate self care. being your biggest ally and ultimate advocate in this journey called life.
name: Ren√©e Sher-McMeans, MFT

so how do we find a way through? perhaps it is my social work background but a cultural and global shift is needed in this very polarized world. and also i think it is impoant to look at the internalized messages we have swallowed and begin to give voice to our truths. there is power in knowing what you know and speaking your truth in the face of others who take an opposing position. your truth is valid, your feelings do not need an explanation or justification. you owe it to yourself and others to take a stand for who you are and what you believe in. and observe how others respond to you, it will tell you a lot about them. we go on and on about self care, to me this is the ultimate self care. being your biggest ally and ultimate advocate in this journey called life.

text:
‚Äúon june 21, after he had finished a draft and incorporated some changes from adams, jefferson had a copy delivered to franklin, with a cover note far more polite than editors generally receive today. "will doctor franklin be so good as to peruse it," he wrote, "and suggest such alterations as his more enlarged view of the subject will dictate?" franklin made only a few small changes, but one of them was resounding. using heavy backslashes, he crossed out the last three words of jefferson‚Äôs phrase, "we hold these truths to be sacred and undeniable" and changed it to read: "we hold these truths to be self-evident." the concept of "self-evident" truths came less from jefferson‚Äôs favored philosopher, locke, than from the scientific determinism of isaac newton and the analytic empiricism of franklin‚Äôs close friend david hume. hume had distinguished between "synthetic" truths that describe matters of fact (such as "london is bigger than philadelphia" ) and "analytic" truths that are self-evident by virtue of reason and definition. ("the angles of a triangle equal 180 degrees" or "all bachelors are unmarried." ) when he chose the word "sacred," jefferson had suggested intentionally or unintentionally that the principle in questionthe equality of men and their endowment by their creator with inalienable rightswas an assertion of religion. by changing it to "self-evident," franklin made it an assertion of rationality.‚Äù
maybe it did take someone with franklin‚Äôs yearsand scientific interestsand experience--to write that phrase. it was, simply, genius. jujutsu. with one word‚Äúself-evident‚Äùfranklin forever clarified the divide between received and rational truth, and placed our political system firmly on the foundation of our common rationality rather than on sectarian faith (and all faiths, even the most popular, are by definition sectarian). it‚Äôs a phrase--a word--that we might profitably ponder again today. franklin was not editing the declaration--he was editing our minds.‚Äù

text:
storytelling is a powerful method of persuasion. its often inherently emotional undertones allow it to be much more effective in overcoming confirmation bias than cold statistics or data. 
in addition, stories allow us not only to learn,¬†but to experience. they bring newfound perspectives into our lives and enrichen our understandings of the world around us. 
because of this, stories are among the most powerful tools in activism.

we invite you to share yours. it can be as detailed or as vague as you feel comfortable. 
if you would like to share your #metoo, #whyididntreport or #timesup story for us to post, you can submit it to our dm or to the forum link in our bio. the forum will not collect your email address. 
you have the option of remaining anonymous and we will not post any information without your explicit consent. 
thank you -boise believes

text:
we are thrilled to share that dalila valdez renteria, our #ignitefellow for southern california, is joining us for a second year! follow our story today for her takeover to learn about what's she done with ignite and what she hopes to do in the coming year.
.
.
. 
more about dalila: dalila is passionate about creating social change through political advocacy. she recently completed her masters of public policy at uc riverside. during her undergraduate career at the university of california, riverside, dalila was an inaugural member of the 2015-2016 college council in southern ca and also led the efforts to launch an ignite chapter on that campus. before serving as a fellow, dalila served as a certified sexual assault counselor and prevention specialist with the riverside area rape crisis center working with young women ages 12-18 to teach them about healthy relationships, sexual harassment prevention and the intersectionalities of violence. dalila is eager to empower more young women to take their next step to elected office to increase the representation of women of color in local government. .
.
.

text:
it‚Äôs free! for a limited time, my award-winning novel, words, is free to readers new to my novels. link in profile.
‚Ä¢
but ‚Äúfree‚Äù begs a question: why? it‚Äôs a question i‚Äôve spent a lot of time considering.
‚Ä¢
at first the answer was what you might expect: a list-building strategy. but that answer neither fully resonates nor represents. that‚Äôs not who i am. maybe, as an author, it‚Äôs who i should be, but...not with this book.
‚Ä¢
this book, and all the struggle it represents‚Äîyears of suffering‚Äîwas ultimately a gift to me. a redemptive gift. use it to build my email list? no. so i let the idea go. but instead of leaving, the idea pestered like an impatient toddler. ‚Ä¢
so i reconsidered, and dug deep. ‚Ä¢
the altruistic answer? at least as altruistic as this oft divided heart can offer, is this: in this era of #metoo, words offers a measure of hope and healing for survivors, and a picture of love for those who walk alongside them. i‚Äôve heard those statements from readers over and over again. ‚Ä¢
words is a story i lived. because of that story, i lost my voice. oftentimes, i still struggle to find my voice. it‚Äôs most elusive in the public marketplace. but make no mistake, when you read words, those characters‚Äô voices are my voice, in all its brokenness. and in hard wrought health. it is a voice ultimately redeemed by the one true redeemer.
‚Ä¢
i believe the message of this book with all my heart: the truth will set you free. and we all need the truth. i want this message to reach as many readers as possible. ‚Ä¢
and yes, i‚Äôll ask for your email address. but you‚Äôre welcome to unsubscribe from my list any time.
‚Ä¢
finally... if you‚Äôre afraid this story of abuse (and healing) may trigger your own trauma, know this: it may. i trust you to make the best choice for you. however, if it‚Äôs time to take another step toward health, grab a trusted friend or counselor and read together. and also know this: it‚Äôs you i prayed for as i wrote. ‚ù§Ô∏è
‚Ä¢
#christianfiction #amreading #metoo #thetruthwillsetyoufree

text:
#halo #hola #yonce #healing #justice

have you ever watched this video, "man down," by #rihanna, the founder of #fenty who was also named harvard's #philanthropist of the year in 2017 and just turned down performing at the #superbowl to show solidarity with #blacklivesmatter as a global movement and #colinkaepernick as a sacred vision on and off the field?

try it now.

here's what i sense as i watch the video, its words and story. the woman in the video, rihanna, recounts how she came to murder a man in public. she was raped. the rape isn't shown. it is alluded to through direct cuts between a man holding her mouth as he presses her against a wall and she struggles and then her body sliding down the wall as she crumples, literally, to the earth.

now, if you know the #statistics for intimate violence such as #rape, #incest, and #assault, you know how common it is. if you're a #survivor, you also know that a rape, for example, doesn't just happen once. it happens in flashes of memory all the time if you have yet to heal or are denied healing. #metoo. #timesup. #kavanope. #insurance.

part of what is so beautiful about this video, which is haunting in its honesty, is that it also showcases how #trauma expands its #socialimpact. #financialmarkets. #financeandeconomy.

now, if you know the statistics for women who have been incarcerated, you know that an overwhelming number of them are there for protecting themselves against their abusers. you also know that women survivors are the most vulnerable after leaving their abusers. you also know that men who murder the women who leave receive far lighter sentences than their female or trans counterparts. #prisonabolition.#metoomvmt. #accounting.

text:
‚Ä¢within those 1 and half year, i managed to repair and break my heart again maybe a thousand times. our relationship was a serious of constant train weeks that somehow we ended up surviving together, hand in hand. the definition of "us" was thrilling and exotic, but dangerous and destructive at the same time. one day we hated each other- "fuck you, don't ever talk to me again." but the very next day we needed each other- "i love you. i miss you. stay with me."
we were toxic to each other, yet, bought peace to each other at the same time- makes no sense, right? i know. 
i'm still trying to make sense of it myself that why we broke up?‚Ä¢üíî

text:
here's a picture of a super fat slug next to my shoe, a happy picture. several of my friends have shared their stories and it's inspired me to make this post. so here goes...
sexual trauma has fucked up more of my life than i ever imagined it could. when trump, a man who bragged about sexually assaulting women was elected president, i literally wanted to kill myself. sexual assault, sexual harassment, and sexual violence are pervasive and insidious crimes. i never reported anything that happened to me for reasons ranging from feeling like it was my fault, to being scared, to it being my word vs. his, to overall being terrified of the process. it's extremely hard to even talk about sexual assault much less to report it. seeing the kavanaugh hearings and trump mock dr. baisley-ford at a campaign rally to the cheers of his supporters is so appalling i don't even have words for it. what i can say however, is that between the political climate, the news, and the general climate of the country, many, many, many survivors are forced to relive their trauma every day. so to all survivors out there, men, women, and everything in between, you are not alone. stay strong, hang in there, and vote. we need to make our voices heard and one way to do it even if we aren't ready to tell our stories, is to vote for people who take this issue seriously, and are willing to fight to change the way things are, regardless of their party affiliations. 
#believethesurvivors #believewomen #believethem #staystrong #vote #youarenotalone #metoo #survivor

sexual trauma has fucked up more of my life than i ever imagined it could. when trump, a man who bragged about sexually assaulting women was elected president, i literally wanted to kill myself. sexual assault, sexual harassment, and sexual violence are pervasive and insidious crimes. i never reported anything that happened to me for reasons ranging from feeling like it was my fault, to being scared, to it being my word vs. his, to overall being terrified of the process. it is extremely hard to even talk about sexual assault much less to report it. seeing the kavanaugh hearings and trump mock dr. baisley-ford at a campaign rally to the cheers of his supporters is so appalling i do not even have words for it. what i can say however, is that between the political climate, the news, and the general climate of the country, many, many, many survivors are forced to relive their trauma every day. so to all survivors out there, men, women, and everything in between, you are not alone. stay strong, hang in there, and vote. we need to make our voices heard and one way to do it even if we are not ready to tell our stories, is to vote for people who take this issue seriously, and are willing to fight to change the way things are, regardless of their party affiliations. 
#believethesurvivors #believewomen #believethem #staystrong #vote #youarenotalone #metoo #survivor

üëèüèΩ #42 üëèüèΩ #oya üëèüèΩ#maat üëèüèΩ#flood üëèüèΩ#justice üëèüèΩ @wocsolidarity üëèüèΩ have you ever watched this video, "man down," by #rihanna, the founder of #fenty who was also named harvard's #philanthropist of the year in 2017 and just turned down performing at the #superbowl to show solidarity with #blacklivesmatter as a global movement and #colinkaepernick as a sacred vision on and off the field?

try it now.

here's what i sense as i watch the video, its words and story. the woman in the video, rihanna, recounts how she came to murder a man in public. she was raped. the rape isn't shown. it is alluded to through direct cuts between a man holding her mouth as he presses her against a wall and she struggles and then her body sliding down the wall as she crumples, literally, to the earth.

now, if you know the #statistics for intimate violence such as #rape, #incest, and #assault, you know how common it is. if you're a #survivor, you also know that a rape, for example, doesn't just happen once. it happens in flashes of memory all the time if you have yet to heal or are denied healing. #metoo. #timesup. #kavanope. #insurance.

part of what is so beautiful about this video, which is haunting in its honesty, is that it also showcases how #trauma expands its #socialimpact. #financialmarkets. #financeandeconomy.

now, if you know the statistics for women who have been incarcerated, you know that an overwhelming number of them are there for protecting themselves against their abusers. you also know that women survivors are the most vulnerable after leaving their abusers. you also know that men who murder the women who leave receive far lighter sentences than their female or trans counterparts. #prisonabolition. #metoomvmt. #accounting.
name: darshan elena campos

text:
on october 17th, lady gaga attended elle women in hollywood event. she wore an oversized suit that day and also delivered a powerful speech. all she shared, through her outfit and her words, is strong power in women.
reports have pointed out that the exaggerated and fancy costumes she wore before are the media that she utilize to give her voices back. why she has done this is because she was sexually assaulted when she was 19 years old. in the speech, it was too painful for her to expose the name who assault her. however, what she has done that day has talked everything‚Äîshe survived and she took back her right to speak.
a suit does not signal masculine. menswear-inspired suit for women actually not only convey women can be strong as men, even stronger, but also signifies that‚Äîwomen are not under the control of men.
back to sexual assault issue, with #metoo movement lasting a year, women have started to express their miserable experience. i can get the feeling of how they endured for these years and how hopeless and helpless they are when they felt ashamed of this experience‚Äîspeechless, and nowhere to outlet. however, actually, i‚Äôve been thinking about that it‚Äôs really hard to draw a line to distinguish whether the one is a monster or a crush at that moment. it‚Äôs obvious that there are differences between women and men, thus perhaps sometimes it‚Äôs the right feeling for men instead of women. of course, men can be assaulted by women. this is an obscure and blurred line.
under this circumstances, as a man, i feel afraid of being a man. stories can be tortured when there are no evidence to prove one‚Äôs innocence. certainly, i am not a supporter of brett kavanaugh or dr. luke(who was accused of assaulting a female singer, kesha). the scars do matter, but people still need to calm down to clarify what has happened. a monster would defend itself and no apology to the victims, while a man who was not intended to attack people would apologize genuinely.  this is a chaotic world‚Äîpeople claim what they want. certainly, this is serious issue that no one would joke about. i suggest this is a time for people to think and discuss instead of saying emotionally and tearing unity

text:
*the me too movement* post 1

for last few days, we all have been hearing a lot of stories and incidents that people have been coming ahead and sharing as a part of #metoo movement. i did not talk much about it because i knew talking about it will stirr up some real strong emotions - some demons that i had chosen to bury deep inside me will surface and haunt me again. but if today i keep quiet, i will probably never be able to forgive myself if, i wish not, but if ever my daughters go through a similar trauma and have no courage to come up to me or someone who can take action and talk about it. so for the sake of my daughters and million other daughters, who do not deserve to suffer in silence, i have decided to open up and write a series of posts about things that happened to people i know, friends and family, to myself .. about incidents that need to be brought to public light to let everyone know what kind of evil exists around us and how as parents, as individuals we need to educate our kids to stand up against these evil and not be those evil themselves! 
the cry for help is my own! may be i just need to put my heart out there to forever get rid of those scarred memories, those horrifying nightmares and the demons i have been trying to supress and hide forever. 
it's time!!!! if you too have a perspective or story you would want me to share, dm me and i'll post it anonymous! 
p.s. - the picture used is a handmade painting by @meinaalsharma 
#metoomovement #harrassment #openup #letstalk #noshame #nothingtobeashamedof #notscaredanymore #mother #daughters #motherofdaughters #parentingdoneright #support #community #standupforyourself #belief

text: this is a long post.. more of a post than a pic since my pic is too faded given the burden of emotion i was under while trying to click this pic.. this pic is for the #unsungheroes in our life.. and i'm gender specific on that word.. for the #men who have been ignored for that one small act that they do #nonchalantly and then just want to get away acting like it wasn't a big deal.. simply bcos it was.. this is a #metoo #moment of a different kind.. for those who #protected us from having another dreaded memory added to our lives.. bcos the sexual predators are out there.. but so are the silent angels.. who come from out of the blue and create a small distraction on our current canvas.. it could be as loud as physically assaulting the perpetrator, or something as quiet as coming between the point of view of discomfort, a glare or a quizzical stare, putting their arm around us or just standing there behind to assure that we're not alone.. a shout out for every single guy known and unknown, who has graced my life and silently proven to me that there is more good on this earth than evil.. who have been the reason i am brave enough to do #latenights or #solotripping, to live the life i want to live.. #philosophy after another nearly escaping another #metoo #brightsideoflife is that some #menareawesome #whatwouldwedowithoutyou

text: every parent should have a few frequently asked questions that allow them to determine whether your child feels safe around the people you've allowed into their lives. they should be opened ended questions that you casually interject into conversations so they don't feel like they're being interrogated. your response should not be to automatically defend the person being discussed, but to allow your child to express how they experience that person and give context for why they feel that way the best they can. look for cues in their body language, facial expression and tone when they hear the person's name or speak about them. try asking "how does grandpa make you feel?" "is there anything about uncle jim's visits that you don't like?" "tell me what you like or don't like about spending time with pastor smith" "does your teacher make you feel safe?" "what do think about susie's dad?" children who are being sexually abused may not be able to directly tell you what is happening to them, but through casual conversation, they may give you clues that something isn't right and you can then investigate further to get to the bottom of it. remember, these are fact finding questions and your child is only going to feel comfortable freely expressing their feelings if you give them the freedom to do so without judgment or the immediate need to change their opinion about the person.  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
as the @dalailama reputedly said, ‚Äúthe world will be saved by the western woman...‚Äù and sure enough, as if the disaffected male, aka this summer‚Äôs mars retrograde, handed the baton over to the girls or female archetype for the venus retrograde to do the work.
whilst venus r is live, the changes and activity we wanted to happen earlier, have every chance of taking place due to several planetary bodies about to change signs - we are at the tipping point, as they hang about the final or early degrees of each sign.
chiron just reverted back to pisces and uranus retrograde is sitting at 0‚Äô taurus, positively waiting to explode, bang on this week‚Äôs taurus full moon, and opposing venus retrograde herself.
juno the marriage broker is also at 0‚Äô waiting to step backward into taurus actually on the day of the full moon.  and the the north node in leo is back-tracking into cancer, whilst circe has just moved into 0‚Äô sag and will soon be followed by jupiter.
so much cosmic change occurring this autumn is handing the steering wheel to venus‚Äô journey to the dark side, demonstrating to those that are braving the depths of scorpio with her, that if you are prepared to dig deep and ask for what your heart desires, then sooner or later, it can really happen.
venus and her female archetype (of either sex), is ready to prove the dalai lama right.
